Pros:. 1) Incredible sound quality.. 2) Sexy- really easy on the eyes.. 3) Reasonable price.. 4) Actually has a screen.. 5) Extremely easy to sync music.. 6) Removable clip is a nice feature.. 
Cons:. 1) Only 1 gig of memory- good for about 50 songs. Not for the extravagant downloaders.. 2) Menus look nice enough, but navigation is a hassle.. 3) Battery life sucks.. 4) Not very durable at all.. 5) USB cable supplied isn't worth your time.. 
Summary:. This was the first name-brand, popular MP3 player I ever purchased. I didn't know much about it, but a friend at school showed me his, and I fell in love with it. So, I got one of my own. It was wonderful - until the USB port started malfunctioning and wouldn't charge the Sansa. But, for the time I had it, I loved it. Here's why:. 1) The sound quality was the most impressive of any small MP3 - and all the other MP3- players I've ever owned.. 2) The Sansa looks like a quality player, with a brilliant outer shell and lit screen.. 3) For an MP3 player with as many features as the Sansa Clip, this comes pretty cheap.. 4) One of the features that the Sansa has over the iPod Shuffle is that it has a screen. Not the best screen, but hey, take it or leave it.. 5) This player syncs music more quickly and more easily than any other player I've owned. It will convert almost any type of file. Nice.. 6) The removable clip is handy.. Ok, let's move onto the cons:. 1) There's only 1 gigabyte of memory in this little player, which is understandable for its size. But still, it has a very limited space, and that is a little flustering.. 2) The menus look nice, but navigating through them is somewhat irritating, and it's hard to see where you're going.. 3) The battery life was nothing impressive, which was a let-down.. 4) It's very delicate, and won't survive many bumps.. 5) The USB cable was so short that the player wouldn't even touch the floor. It broke as well, rendering me unable to charge the player.. For the short time that I owned it, the Sandisk Sansa Clip was the best player I had ever owned. Would I trade it in for my Zune? Heck, no. But if you're on a budget and you're not one for downloading tons of music (although, you could always get the 8 gig version), then I would recommend the Clip. Highly. It's the best budget player you could possibly buy.. 

$$;
Pros:. This is a tiny player. Sansa built this device well--if you pull on the clip wrong, it just detaches instead of snapping off and breaking. The display is a beautiful bright blue color that shows up well at night.. 
Cons:. I love this player, but it's battery stopped holding a charge exactly a year after I bought it, so the warranty was void. Now the thing plays only five songs on a full charge before turning off. Also, it's hard to set the equalizer appropriately.. 
Summary:. An okay player. No playlist support (like just about everything but the iPod, sadly). Still, I loved the player because of its low price ($30 on Black Friday), but its untimely death has me wondering if I can ever trust an mp3 player with an irreplaceable internal battery. It's not just Sansa--I've been through two iPods, and one of them had the same issue. With a one-year-only warranty, Sansa has left me high and dry without an mp3 player.. 

